        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <date>July 28. 77.</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am much obliged for your kind and courteous letter. From what I have observed in various periodicals I can see that the discussion of the Philosophy of Evolution is at present very important. In the course of a few days I will read what you have been so kind as to point out to me with reference to instinct.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>I remain, with much respect | Yours faithfully | Charles Darwin.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Carneri’s letter has not been found. Carneri had previously sent CD copies of his works on morality, psychology, and Darwinism (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 19, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7695F.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Bartholomäus von Carneri, 17 April [1871]</ref>, and <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 24, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10466F.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Bartholomäus von Carneri, 22 April 1876</ref>). Carneri was probably working on his <hi rend="italic">Grundlegung der Ethik</hi> (Foundation of ethics, <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9563.xml" resp="#automat" cert="low">Carneri [1880]</ref>; see letter from <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_835.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Bartholomäus von Carneri</ref>, 30 October 1880 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1163.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Calendar</hi></ref> no. 12784).</note>
        </div>        
            
